default&#xa0;defaultWhat should the BBC be for and defaultwhat should be the purpose of publicdefault defaultservice broadcasting?default&#xa0;
defaultPerhaps the easiest way to approach the first limb of this question is to ask
default 
defaultʻ
defaultWhat should the BBC 
defaultnot
default be for?ʼ.
default&#xa0;
defaultMy 
defaulthigh level 
defaultanswer to this reversed question is both simple and emphatic:
default 
defaultthe BB
defaultC should not exist to provide the type and quality of radio, TV and
default 
defaultonline content that is, or could be, provided by commercial media
default 
defaultorganisations.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf the BBC does little or nothing of significance over and above mimicking
default 
defaultprivate sector media organisati
defaultons, then it has no reason to exist at all.
default&#xa0;
defaultAnd for the avoidance of doubt, the veracity of this observation is in no way
default 
defaultlessened because the BBC happens to be a giant news and current affairs
default 
defaultorganisation. Clearly, a raison dʼêtre
default for the BBC cannot reside in its size
default 
defaultalone.
default&#xa0;
defaultA further question thus arises, namely ʻDoes the BBC do anything of
default 
defaultsignificance that could not readily be done by other media organisations?ʼ.
default&#xa0;
defaultI address this further question in my answer below to the Commit
defaultteeʼs
default 
defaultquestion concerning the scope, scale and remit of the BBC.
defaultHow well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period indefault defaultachieving its mission and public purposes?default&#xa0;
defaultBeing but an ordinary viewer and listener, I was not familiar with the concept of
default 
defaultthe BBCʼs mission but the BBC website soon informed me that the BBC has a
default 
defaultMission ʻto enrich peopleʼs lives with programmes and services that inform,
default 
defaulteducate and entertainʼ.
default&#xa0;
defaultI am obliged to the BBC in seeking to enrich me because my annual TV tax
default 
defaulttogether
default with that of a multitude of others certainly enriches many senior
default 
defaultmanagers and celebrities at the BBC.
default&#xa0;
defaultGoogling the term ʻpublic purposesʼ immediately located it for me as being in
default 
defaultthe BBC Charter. I was thus able to observe that the first Public Purpose
default of the
default 
defaultBBC is ʻsustaining citizenship and civil societyʼ. I was left wondering if the
default 
defaultcitizen is to exclaim “Gosh, what a wondrous thing is the BBC” or whether he
default 
defaultis to think to himself “Crikey, a bit Orwellian that!”.
default&#xa0;
defaultMy seeking enlightenment in this 
defaultvein also yielded an insight into the ways in
default 
defaultwhich the BBC Trust attempts to impart to the management the strategy that
default 
defaultthe Trust has formulated and the tools that have been constructed for
default 
defaultattempting to monitor the performance of the management. In this 
defaultcontext I
default 
defaultobserved that there exist 
defaultinter alia 
defaultStrategic Objectives whereby, for example,
default 
defaultthe Trust ʻchallengesʼ the BBC to increase the distinctiveness and quality of
default 
defaultoutput, Service Licences, Protocols, Public Purposes and Purpose Remits,
default 
defaultAnnual Tracking
default Surveys, Statements of Programme Policy and Summary
default 
defaultWorkplans.
default&#xa0;
defaultI conclude that the objectives given to the BBC by the Charter (plus
default 
defaultFramework Agreement) are largely of a high-flown flannel nature and that the
default 
defaultmachinery for setting the direction of the BB
defaultC and for assessing performance
default 
defaultis so hideously bureaucratic and so formulaic when put into practice that
default 
defaultmeaningful results are hardly to be expected.
default&#xa0;
defaultFor these reasons I am unable to provide a direct answer to the subject
default 
defaultquestion. I would, however, lik
defaulte to attempt to provide some relevant
default 
defaultobservations to the Committee, and these now follow.
default&#xa0;
defaultI suggest that it is very useful in examining the BBCʼs performance to adopt a
default 
defaultlong timescale and to concentrate on television services.
default&#xa0;
defaultUp until the mid-1950s the
default BBC had a monopoly in TV and I distinctly remember, although I was a teenager, my apprehension when it was announced that commercial TV was to be introduced. I was worried that commercial TV would affect deleteriously the standards of BBC TV. 
default&#xa0;
defaultI cannot p
defaultretend to remember the exact chronology, but the upshot over a
default 
defaultcertain timescale was as feared. The BBC did not stand firm on quality
default 
defaultstandards, but gave in to the temptation of attempting to maintain ratings as
default 
defaultagainst what it perceived to be rival servic
defaultes.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe psychology of the BBCʼs reaction to the inception of commercial TV could
default 
defaultnot be more simple. The BBC bigwigs apprehended that the punters who paid
default 
defaultthe bigwigsʼ salaries and underpinned the bigwigsʼ careers would begin to
default 
defaultcomplain if they had to 
defaultpay compulsorily a licence fee for programmes the
default 
defaultviewership figures of which fell below those of the commercial services.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe adoption of the ratings chasing policy was thus driven by a desire for self
default-
defaultpreservation.
default 
defaultIn the demotic the policy goes, of cou
defaultrse, by the name of ʻratings
default 
defaultwarʼ. The BBC became adept at fighting the ratings war and it has maintained
default 
defaultto the present day its view that being active in that war is vital to the BBCʼs
default 
defaultcontinued existence.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis plain and simple fact about the BBC is publ
defaulticly admitted by very few of
default 
defaultour parliamentarians. Indeed, the flow over the years of MPs and peers who
default 
defaultget upon their feet to proclaim that the BBC provides the ʻgold standardʼ of
default 
defaultbroadcasting quality has never ceased.
default&#xa0;
defaultIs it a prerequisite of being a pol
defaultitician that one can selectively fail to see
default 
defaultelephants in the room? Whatever the answer to that question, the fact is that
default 
defaultwhilst operating ostensibly under strict requirements as to the maintenance of
default 
defaulthigh standards, the BBC has in fact been permitted for
default sixty years, and by all
default 
defaultparties, to consistently produce a general output at that low level which is
default 
defaultdictated by ratings considerations.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis means that scandalously the public have been, and still are being,
default 
defaultcharged, on a compulsory basis, for a sub-sta
defaultndard product.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat scope, scale and remit should the BBC have?default&#xa0;
defaultAs I intimated in my answer to the first question, the BBC should be
default 
defaultgiven scope, scale and remit only if it can provide output which is significantly
default 
defaultdifferent from that which is deliverable by other organisations, including
default 
defaultcommercial companies. A requirement additional to difference is, of course,
default 
defaultpublic value.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs I explained with reference to the second question, albeit that the BBC operates under a
default cloak of ultra-respectable Public Purposes etc., it has in fact over a very long period chosen to maintain a dumbed down output as its continuous response to the output of what it sees as its rivals.
default&#xa0;
defaultHere then we have a problematic situation. In choosing
default to dumb down its
default 
defaultoutput to bolster its programme ratings the BBC has 
defaultipso facto 
defaultbrought itself
default 
defaultdown to the level of its rivals. And in doing this, it has extinguished any
default 
defaultjustification for claiming to be significantly different from its rivals.
default&#xa0;
defaultAt this j
defaultuncture perhaps I hear members of the Committee saying “But what
default 
defaultabout the BBCʼs output of news and current affairs?”. “Surely everyone
default 
defaultacknowledges the BBCʼs pre-eminence in that sphere”.
default&#xa0;
defaultWell, let us consider a comparison of the quality of a commercial 
defaultTV news
default 
defaultservice, Sky News, and a prominent BBC TV news service, BBC News 24.
default&#xa0;
defaultIt cannot be seriously said that one of these services is significantly
default 
defaultsuperior or significantly inferior to the other. Individuals may, of course, favour
default 
defaultone over the other bec
defaultause of personal preference or merely through
default 
defaulthabit.
default&#xa0;
defaultHere it is pertinent to note from the statistical section (pp. 14 &amp; 15) that
default 
defaultwhen it comes to users of the most used TV news sources, most rate
default 
defaultthem reasonably highly in respect of accuracy, trustworthi
defaultness and impartiality.
default 
defaultAnd, as the table on page 15 shows, the news services of ITV and Sky are
default 
defaultrated very much on a par with those of the BBC.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe broadcast media have from their inception been seen as potent in their
default 
defaultpotential for upholding the democrat
defaultic values of this country but representing
default 
defaultequally potently a threat to democracy should they to come under undesirable
default 
defaultcontrol. At the nub of these considerations is the broadcasting of news.
default&#xa0;
defaultPoliticians, in providing for an appropriate framework for the
default operation of the
default 
defaultbroadcast media, have thus put special effort into attempting to ensure that all
default 
defaultradio and TV organisations which broadcast news items do so in a fair,
default 
defaultaccurate, impartial etc. manner. Indeed, it may be said that the provision of
default 
defaultnews acc
defaultording to these criteria lies at the very heart of the concept of public
default 
defaultservice broadcasting, whether one has in mind the BBC or the public service
default 
defaultobligations of the other broadcasters.
default&#xa0;
defaultThus if it is the case that the public see BBC news provision as on
default a level with
default 
defaultthe news provision of other providers, that is, if it does not see the BBCʼs news
default 
defaultprovision as being distinctly more accurate, trustworthy and impartial, then the
default 
defaultBBC has failed the 
defaultAcid Test of Differentiation
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf there was any question of 
defaultthe TV news output of non-BBC organisations
default 
defaultbeing significantly inferior to that of the BBC as judged on the crucial criteria
default 
defaultaforementioned, this would be a matter of loud, prolonged and general debate,
default 
defaultnot least,
default 
defaultof course, on prog
defaultr
defaultammes such as 
defaultQuestion
default Time. 
defaultNo such debate
default 
defaultexists.
default&#xa0;
defaultNow as I have already pointed out, in choosing to engage in the ratings war
default 
defaultthe BBC has had to generally dumb down its output to the level of its rivals. As
default 
defaultto whether this general dumbing down includes the BBCʼs news and rel
defaultated
default 
defaultprogrammes can be left for debate, because as has been established the BBC
default 
defaultfails the news-specific 
defaultAcid Test of Differentiation.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe logic thus is that the BBC does not warrant scope, scale or remit because
default 
defaultits continued existence cannot be justified
default on PSB grounds.
default&#xa0;
defaultThat is not to say that the continued existence of the BBC at a drastically
default 
defaultreduced scale (size) might not be justified. On this basis I will now make some
default 
defaultremarks on the present size and scope of activities of the BBC and as to what
default 
defaultmight be an appropriate size/scope in the future.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn my consideration of the size/scope of the present BBC I have in mind the
default 
defaultBBC as a provider of radio, TV and online services.
default&#xa0;
defaultMy contention is that the BBC is far too big. In my view the BBC has been
default 
defaultpe
defaultrmitted to grow to such an extent that it now constitutes a danger to vital
default 
defaultelements of the UK media industry including commercial radio and TV,
default 
defaultnational and local, and to local and national newspapers. The BBC is a grave
default 
defaultimpediment to the establishment of
default a healthily diverse media scene in the UK.
default&#xa0;
defaultI will not dwell on the deleterious effects that BBC TV and radio are having on
default 
defaultthe general media because I am certain that others far more authoritative than
default 
defaultI will make submissions to the Committee. All that I
default will do is to underline the
default 
defaultfact that it is only in a healthily diverse media scene that the public are
default 
defaultexposed to a range of different opinions, views and information from a variety
default 
defaultof sources.
