default 
defaultprovision of internet news using the licence fee. This makes it enormously difficult for
default 
defaultlocal newspapers to compete. If the BBC can, as they do, provide all t
defaulthe locally
default 
defaultsignificant news, what is left to motivate the local reader to buy a paper?
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is destroying local newspapers and it could eventually happen to national
default 
defaultnewspapers as well.
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is dangerous for local politics as it is for local journalism.”
default&#xa0;
default“This is a debate that wonʼt go away and I believe that the BBC has to think carefully
default 
defaultabout its presence locally and the impact that has on local democracy.”
default&#xa0;
defaultNo doubt Mrs May, as a senior cabinet minister, was being somewhat circumspect with her comments
default on the BBCʼs online services, but she certainly identified a grave threat to the print media, both local and national. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the years running up to the commencement of the present Charter it may have
default 
defaultappeared simply logical to permit the TV tax funded BBC
default to extent itself onto the
default 
defaultnew online platform. But with the advantage of hindsight we can see that what the
default 
defaultpoliticians did in giving the thumbs-up was rather like that done, with equal facility, by
default 
defaultthe Sorcererʼs Apprentice.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhereas news services of the
default broadcast media are regulated as to impartiality, the
default 
defaultnewspapers are left to grind whatever political or other axe their proprietors fancy.
default 
defaultThus from a political point of view we have on the left the Daily Mirror, the Financial
default 
defaultTimes, the Guardian and the
default Independent, on the right the Daily Express, the Daily
default 
defaultMail and the Telegraph and with a flexible approach (over time) to position on the
default 
defaultpolitical spectrum the Sun and the Times.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe freedom of the press to choose attitudes to news items and issues 
defaultprovides the
default 
defaultpublic with an opportunity to be made aware of a wide range of arguments and
default 
defaultopinions and is 
defaultat the very heart of our democracy in the UK
default.
defaultTherefore any news media entity which poses an existential threat to the newspaper
default 
defaultindustry, whether in 
defaultrespect of printed newspapers or online services, must be
default 
defaultexamined by Parliament with the upmost seriousness and 
defaulturgency, this being all the
default 
defaultmore the case when the entity in question is a public sector entity and thus one
default 
defaultwhich is within the direct sphere 
defaultof influence of Parliament.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn looking to the future, I am not at all sure what would be an appropriate remit for
default 
defaultthe BBC. As I have indicated above, in the present era there would appear to no
default 
defaultmore justification for a nationalised broadcaster and online 
defaultoperator than there is for
default 
defaulta public sector newspaper.
default&#xa0;
defaultI do not, of course, expect to see the BBC disappear suddenly, but it is important to
default 
defaultthe future of democracy in our country that as soon as possible it is drastically
default 
defaultdecreased both in scope and scale
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn its present form the BBC is stifling media diversity and threatening the continued
default 
defaultexistence of our newspapers. This means that the BBC constitutes a threat to our
default 
defaultdemocracy.
default&#xa0;
defaultA much reduced BBC, or a successor organisation, could have one of a numbe
defaultr of
default 
defaultprofiles, but as an indicator I would suggest that the following would be appropriate.
default&#xa0;
defaultTV default defaultOne general channel approximating to an amalgam of present BBC One and
default 
defaultBBC Four, plus BBC Parliament Channel. No regional/local TV services.
default&#xa0;
defaultRadio default defaultTwo
default national channels, approximating respectively to present channels 4 and
default 
default3. No local stations.
default&#xa0;
defaultOnline default defaultExcepting for content strictly connected with BBC services, such as
default 
defaultprogramme listings, BBC Online should be cut away from the BBC to form a
default 
defaultseparate en
defaulttity funded by subscription. An alternative would be a separation of BBC
default 
defaultNews, including online news, from the remainder of the BBC, again funded by
default 
defaultsubscription.
default&#xa0;
defaultMy indications of a future BBC or successor will to some appear over-drastic, but
default 
defaultsuch is th
defaulte state of the present BBC that in the interests of a healthy democracy it is
default 
defaultin dire need of brutal surgery.
default&#xa0;
defaultReturning to the question of remit, in the light of my observations all I can advise is
default 
defaultthat any new Public Purposes or the like are couched in 
defaultterms less Orwellian and
default 
defaultless high-flown than is the case in the present Charter. I would also put in a plea that
default 
defaultthe Big Brother/social engineering tenor of the PSB purposes and characteristics set
default 
defaultout by Ofcom in its PSB Annual Report 2013 (Fig. 1) is fi
defaultrmly eschewed.
default&#xa0;
defaultWhat role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways ofdefault defaultdistributing content?default&#xa0;
defaultThe development of technology relating to TV, radio or online and novel modes of
default 
defaultdistributing content/information/data is the province of the 
defaultlikes of Google, Apple and
default 
defaultSamsung, and not that of a UK public sector broadcasting organisation.
default&#xa0;
defaultHow should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?default&#xa0;
defaultThe TV tax is very unpopular, especially in view of the multitude of sources of
default 
defaultinformation and entertainment now 
defaultavailable to the public on TV (and elsewhere).
default&#xa0;
defaultIn my view the idea of imposing a compulsory tax on the UK public in respect of one
default 
defaultout of a multitude of media outlets is a totally unjustified anachronism. Much would
default 
defaultbe the rejoicing among the populace upo
defaultn the lifting of this unfair imposition.
default&#xa0;
defaultLooking at the matter from a different angle, if the BBCʼs current output truly
default 
defaultrepresents the gold standard of quality in broadcasting as some parliamentarians
default 
defaultregularly claim, why should not the BBC be funded, an
defaultd funded only, by the
default 
defaultvoluntary subscriptions of members of the public.
default&#xa0;
defaultAs set forth above, it is clear that the BBCʼs online services in respect of news are
default 
defaultthreatening the continued existence of national and local newspapers. This supplies
default 
defaultanother and v
defaultital reason as to why, if the BBC is to be permitted to continue to put
default 
defaultout news and current affairs online, the BBC should be funded on a subscription
default 
defaultbasis.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have had ample evidence of late as to the BBCʼs talent for wasting TV tax
default 
defaultpayersʼ money as we
defaultll as to other management shortcomings. Thus an advantage of
default 
defaultfunding the BBC on a subscription basis is that the BBC would, for the first time,
default 
defaulthave to earn its income. This would tighten up management.
default&#xa0;
defaultHow should the BBC be governed, regulated and held adefaultccountable?default&#xa0;
defaultIt is surely clear that the replacement of BBC governors by the BBC Trust has been
default 
defaulta true failure. One cannot be surprise at this since any objective person would
default 
defaultperceive immediately that the concept of a body a part of the BBC being 
defaultresponsible
default 
defaultfor overseeing the BBC and at the same time representing the TV tax payer was
default 
defaultdoomed to failure.
default&#xa0;
defaultThus the BBC, whether it is to exist in the near future in its giant, overbearing,
default 
defaultcompetition suppressing , democracy threatening form or not, mu
defaultst be regulated by
default 
defaulta body outside the BBC. Whether that body is Ofcom in its present or a modified
default 
defaultform is a moot point, but future regulation must be external of the BBC.
