defaultUK Media Statisticsdefault&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;
defaultThis statistics section presents statistics 
defaultillustrative of the present shape of the UK
default 
defaultmedia and more especially of the extent of the BBCʼs operations and of the size of
default 
defaultits presence in the UK media world.
default&#xa0;
defaultEmphasis is placed on the provision of news services. The reason for this is simply
default 
defaultthat the
default availability of a plurality of news sources is essential to the healthy working
default 
defaultof a democracy. In this context “plurality” connotes many rather than few news
default 
defaultservices and, just as importantly, the avoidance of any one media organisation
default 
defaulthaving too much i
defaultnfluence over public opinion and over the political process.
default&#xa0;
defaultSeeking to ensure the existence of many and diverse news sources and the
default 
defaultabsence of too much media power in one or a few hands is the only way of
default 
defaultpromoting range and diversity of information and
default opinion.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe statistics have been derived predominantly from Ofcom documents or from
default 
defaultreport documents commissioned by Ofcom. Abbreviations used in the text to refer to
default 
defaultsuch documents are as follows.
default&#xa0;
default“A4” to “A6” -
default              
defaultAnnexes, so respectively referenced, to
default 
defaultMeasuring media plurality,
default 
defaultOfcomʼs advice to DMCS, published 19 June 2012
default&#xa0;
default“CMR13” - 
default              
defaultCommunications Market Report 2013
default, Ofcom Research Document,
default 
defaultpublished 1 August 2013
default&#xa0;
defaultMedia Generallydefault&#xa0;
default91% of UK adults say they follow the news. 78% use TV for news, 40%
default use print
default 
defaultnewspapers, 35% use radio and 32% use the internet (CMR13 1.9.3 &amp; Fig. 1.93).
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen respondents were asked to what extent they used each platform for types of
default 
defaultnews, i.e. serious news items, breaking news, headlines &amp; summaries, opinions &amp;
default 
defaultdebate
defaults and in-depth analysis, TV dominated in each of the 5 categories, only losing
default 
defaultits dominance when it came to light hearted stories and rumour &amp; gossip (A4 Fig. 2).
default&#xa0;
defaultBy way of example, A4 Fig. 2 shows that for serious news 81% said they used TV,
default 
defaultwhereas the
default scores for newspapers, radio and the internet were 42%, 38% &amp; 44%
default 
